.Th "Version 1.0"

.Sh NAME
.Nm simple_shell
\- Simple Unix shell implementation
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Ar gcc -Wall -Werror -Wextra -pedantic -std=gnu89 *.c -o hsh

.B \fB./hsh\fR or
\fBecho "
.Ar [command]"
| ./hsh\fR

.Sh DESCRIPTION
The \fBsimple_shell\fP program is a basic Unix shell written in C, providing a command\-line interface for executing commands. It supports built\-in commands such as \fBexit\fP to terminate the shell and \fBenv\fP to print environment variables.

.Sh COMMANDS
.Bl -tag -width -indent  \" Begins a tagged list
.It \fBexit\fR
Terminate the shell program.
.It \fBenv\fR
Print environment variables.
.El

.Sh FUNCTIONS

.Bl -tag -width -indent  \" Begins a tagged list
.It \fB_getenv(const char *name)\fR               \" Each item preceded by .It macro
Get the value of an environment variable.
.It \fBprint_environment(void)\fR
Print all environment variables.
.It \fBtokenize_input(char *cmd, char *argv[])\fR
Tokenize the input command.
.It \fB_strdup(char *str)\fR
Duplicate a string and return a pointer to the allocated memory.
.It \fBexecute_command(char *cmd)\fR
Execute the given command.
.It \fBfind_and_execute_command(char *argv[])\fR
Find and execute the specified command.
.It \fBexecute_command_with_path(char *command_path, char *argv[])\fR
Execute the command with the specified path.
.El

.Sh RETURN VALUE
The \fBsimple_shell\fP program returns 0 upon successful execution. In case of errors, appropriate error messages are displayed, and the program exits with a non\-zero exit status.

.Sh EXAMPLES
.sp
.Bl -tag -width -indent  \" Begins a tagged list
.It $ ./shell
Run the shell.
.It ($) exit
Exit the shell.
.It ($) env
Print environment variables.
.sp
Simple_shell works in interactive mode:


.Bl -tag -width -indent  \" Begins a tagged list
.It $ ./hsh
.It ($) /bin/ls
.It hsh main.c shell.c
.It ($)
.It ($) exit
.It $
.El
.Pp

And in non-interactive mode:


.Bl -tag -width -indent
.It $ echo "/bin/ls" | ./hsh
.It hsh main.c shell.c test_ls_2
.It $
.It $ cat test_ls_2
.It /bin/ls
.It /bin/ls
.It $
.It $ cat test_ls_2 | ./hsh
.It hsh main.c shell.c test_ls_2
.It hsh main.c shell.c test_ls_2
.It $
.El

.Sh SEE ALSO
\fBsh(1p)\fR, \fBexecve(2)\fR, \fBfork(2)\fR, \fBwait(2)\fR, \fBaccess(2)\fR, \fBstrtok(3)\fR, \fBgetline(3)\fR, \fBmalloc(3)\fR, \fBfree(3)\fR, \fBprintf(3)\fR, \fBstrcmp(3)\fR, \fBstrlen(3)\fR, \fBstrncmp(3)\fR.

